Diagnosis. Females can be distinguished by the broad copulatory hoods that meet medially in the epigyne ( Figs 41 , 65 ) and the copulatory ducts with a nearly perpendicular bend (
Fig. 66
). Males can be recognised by the broad, evenly oblique embolus base and the long fine distal coil of the embolus ( Figs 48 , 67 ).

Distribution. Presently known only from northern KwaZulu-Natal Province (Maputaland), South Africa (
Fig. 68
).
